Preheat your oven to 200 degrees and cut the @cherry tomatoes{1}(halved) in half. Remove
the core from the @yellow pepper{1}(seeded and sliced into strips) and @red pepper{1}(seeded
and sliced into strips). Lay out on a #baking tray{} then drizzle with @olive oil{} and
season with a pinch of @salt{}. Roast on the top shelf of your #oven{} for ~{15-20%minutes}
until starting to brown at the edges.

Boil a #pot{} of water with a pinch of @salt{}. Peel and finely chop the @onion{1/2}(peeled
and finely chopped). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a
#garlic press{} if you have one). Roughly chop the @basil{1/2}(roughly chopped).

Cook the @rigatoni pasta{200%g} in the boiling water for ~{11%minutes} or until 'al dente'.
> 'Al dente' simply means the pasta is cooked through but has a tiny bit of firmness left
> in the middle - taste it as you go to get it just right.
Once cooked drain, reserving a splash of pasta water.

Add a splash of @olive oil{} to a #frying pan{} over medium heat. Once warm, add the
@diced chorizo{1} and onion and cook gently for ~{5%minutes} until soft. Add your
garlic and a few good grinds of @black pepper{} and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Cut the @black olives{30} in half lengthways and add to the pan along with a splash of
the pasta water. Add the @mozzarella{1}(torn) and most, but not all, of your basil. Add
your pasta and toss everything together.

> Adding pasta water is a classic Italian trick and adds some salt and starchiness to
> give you a bit of a sauce.

Serve with your remaining mozzarella torn over the top, the rest of your basil and a
drizzle of @olive oil{}.